A little bit about Bayes itself

I actually care more about the high level take-awayâ€¦

Given 1. (â€œyour priorâ€) what you believe right now about the unknowns (aka parameters, hypothesesâ€¦) youâ€™re trying to learn about/narrow down 2. (â€œyour likelihood modelâ€) your model for how things would look if you knew what the unknowns were Then: Bayes tells you how to update what you believe. You donâ€™t have a choiceâ€“weâ€™re going to calculate it!

Example: â€œI think some data is going to be normally distributedâ€¦ Iâ€™m just not quite sure yet which normal distribution (that is, what its mean and variance are)â€. You have some beliefs (â€œyour priorâ€) about what its mean and variance could be (the unknowns youâ€™d like to learn about), and you think that if only you knew what the mean and variance were, then youâ€™d know what the distribution of new data would be (â€œyour likelihoodâ€): a normal distribution with that mean and variance!

\[ p(H|D) = p(H) \frac{p(D|H)}{p(D)} \]

Another version of Bayesâ€™ rule that I actually kind of prefer is in terms of â€œoddsâ€, the ratio of how probable you think one hypothesis is versus another:

\[ \frac{p(H_1|D)}{p(H_2|D)} = \frac{p(H_1)}{p(H_2)} \cdot \frac{p(D|H_1)}{p(D|H_2)} \]

In words: how you feel relatively speaking about H1 versus H2 used to be p(H1)/p(H2). Now that youâ€™ve seen some new data D, Bayes says you should feel what you used to feelâ€¦ multiplied by p(D|H1)/p(D|H2), known as the â€œlikelihood ratioâ€.

posterior odds of H1 vs.Â H2 = prior odds * likelihood ratio
